1
00:01:30,857 --> 00:01:34,054
This could be the room
of any small boy...

2
00:01:34,127 --> 00:01:38,894
but it just happens to belong
to a boy named Christopher Robin.

3
00:01:38,965 --> 00:01:44,062
Like most small boys, Christopher Robin
has toy animals to play with.

4
00:01:44,137 --> 00:01:49,632
They all live together
in a wonderful world of make-believe.

5
00:01:49,709 --> 00:01:53,907
But his best friend is a bear
called Winnie the Pooh...

6
00:01:53,980 --> 00:01:56,141
or "Pooh" for short.

7
00:01:56,216 --> 00:02:00,016
Now, Pooh had some
very unusual adventures...

8
00:02:00,086 --> 00:02:04,216
and they all happened right here
in the Hundred-Acre Wood.

9
00:02:04,290 --> 00:02:09,159
<i>Deep in the Hundred-Acre Wood</i>

10
00:02:09,229 --> 00:02:14,326
<i>Where Christopher Robin plays</i>

11
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:20,270
<i>You'll find</i>
<i>the enchanted neighborhood</i>

12
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:26,336
<i>Of Christopher's</i>
<i>childhood days</i>

13
00:02:26,412 --> 00:02:31,372
<i>A donkey named Eeyore</i>
<i>is his friend</i>

14
00:02:31,451 --> 00:02:35,888
<i>And Kanga and little Roo</i>

15
00:02:35,955 --> 00:02:39,049
<i>There's Rabbit and Piglet</i>

16
00:02:39,125 --> 00:02:41,252
<i>And there's Owl</i>

17
00:02:41,327 --> 00:02:45,787
<i>But most of all</i>
<i>Winnie the Pooh</i>

18
00:02:45,865 --> 00:02:49,562
<i>Winnie the Pooh</i>
<i>Winnie the Pooh</i>

19
00:02:49,636 --> 00:02:52,799
<i>Tubby little cubby</i>
<i>all stuffed with fluff</i>

20
00:02:52,872 --> 00:02:56,774
<i>He's Winnie the Pooh</i>
<i>Winnie the Pooh</i>

21
00:02:56,843 --> 00:03:00,279
<i>Willy-nilly, silly old bear</i>

22
00:03:00,346 --> 00:03:01,813
- <i>Winnie the Pooh</i>
- Pooh!

23
00:03:01,881 --> 00:03:03,075
- <i>Winnie the Pooh</i>
- Pooh!

24
00:03:03,149 --> 00:03:06,084
<i>Tubby little cubby</i>
<i>all stuffed with fluff</i>

25
00:03:06,152 --> 00:03:09,610
<i>He's Winnie the Pooh</i>
<i>Winnie the Pooh</i>

26
00:03:09,689 --> 00:03:14,786
<i>Willy-nilly, silly old bear</i>

27
00:03:14,928 --> 00:03:19,558
Winnie the Pooh lived
in this enchanted forest...

28
00:03:19,632 --> 00:03:21,463
under the name of"Sanders"...

29
00:03:21,534 --> 00:03:26,130
which means he had the name
over the door in gold letters...

30
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:28,834
and he lived under it.

31
00:03:28,908 --> 00:03:32,071
- Now, when Pooh heard
his "pooh-coo" clock...
- Pooh-coo.

32
00:03:32,145 --> 00:03:37,173
Pooh-coo, pooh-coo, pooh-coo,
pooh-coo, pooh-coo.

33
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:39,810
He knew it was time
for something.

34
00:03:39,886 --> 00:03:42,946
But he was a bear
of very little brain.

35
00:03:43,022 --> 00:03:48,255
So when he thought, he thought in
the most thoughtful way he could think.

36
00:03:48,328 --> 00:03:51,923
I haven't thought of anything,
have you?

37
00:03:51,998 --> 00:03:54,865
Nor neither have I.

38
00:03:54,934 --> 00:03:57,630
Think, think, think.

39
00:04:00,373 --> 00:04:04,173
Oh, yes. Time for
my stoutness exercise.

40
00:04:04,244 --> 00:04:06,940
Up, down, up.

41
00:04:07,013 --> 00:04:10,005
<i>When I up, down</i>
<i>touch the ground</i>

42
00:04:10,083 --> 00:04:13,280
<i>It puts me in the mood</i>

43
00:04:13,353 --> 00:04:15,548
<i>Up, down, touch the ground</i>

44
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:19,456
<i>In the mood for food</i>

45
00:04:19,525 --> 00:04:23,461
<i>I am stout, round</i>
<i>and I have found</i>

46
00:04:23,529 --> 00:04:26,054
<i>Speaking poundage-wise</i>

47
00:04:26,132 --> 00:04:31,399
<i>I improve my appetite</i>
<i>when I exercise</i>

48
00:04:31,471 --> 00:04:33,632
Oh, stuff and fluff.

49
00:04:37,543 --> 00:04:40,137
That's better. Thank you.

50
00:04:40,213 --> 00:04:42,204
Now, where was I?

51
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:51,223
Oh, yes. I'm rumbly in my tumbly.
Time for something sweet.

52
00:04:51,291 --> 00:04:54,988
<i>I am short, fat</i>
<i>and proud of that</i>

53
00:04:55,061 --> 00:04:57,393
<i>So with all my might</i>

54
00:04:57,463 --> 00:04:59,761
<i>I up, down, up, down</i>

55
00:04:59,832 --> 00:05:02,357
<i>To my appetite's delight</i>

56
00:05:02,435 --> 00:05:05,700
<i>While I up, down</i>
<i>touch the ground</i>

57
00:05:05,772 --> 00:05:08,332
<i>I think of things to chew</i>

58
00:05:08,408 --> 00:05:11,104
Like honey and milk
and chocolate.

59
00:05:11,177 --> 00:05:13,509
<i>With a hefty, happy appetite</i>

60
00:05:13,579 --> 00:05:15,740
<i>I'm a hefty, happy pooh</i>

61
00:05:15,815 --> 00:05:19,945
<i>With a hefty, happy appetite</i>
<i>he's a hefty, happy pooh</i>

62
00:05:22,422 --> 00:05:25,448
Oh, bother. Empty again.

63
00:05:25,525 --> 00:05:28,460
Only the sticky part is left.

64
00:05:35,868 --> 00:05:40,805
That buzzing noise
means something.

65
00:05:40,873 --> 00:05:45,640
And the only reason for making
a buzzing noise that I know of...

66
00:05:45,712 --> 00:05:49,478
is because you're a... a bee!

67
00:05:55,021 --> 00:05:59,583
And the only reason for being a bee
is to make honey.

68
00:06:01,561 --> 00:06:04,894
And the only reason for making honey
is so I can eat it.

69
00:06:08,234 --> 00:06:11,499
And so Winnie the Pooh
climbed the honey tree.

70
00:06:11,571 --> 00:06:14,563
He climbed and he climbed
and he climbed.

71
00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:17,837
- And as he climbed,
he hummed a little hum.
- <i>Hum, hum</i>

72
00:06:17,910 --> 00:06:18,934
<i>Hum, hum</i>

73
00:06:19,011 --> 00:06:21,479
And I call it
my "rumbly in my tumbly" song.

74
00:06:21,547 --> 00:06:24,482
Yes, and it went
something like this.

75
00:06:24,550 --> 00:06:27,678
<i>Hum dum de dum</i>
<i>Hum dum de dum</i>

76
00:06:27,754 --> 00:06:30,746
<i>I am so rumbly</i>
<i>in my tumbly</i>

77
00:06:30,823 --> 00:06:32,484
Oh!

78
00:06:32,558 --> 00:06:35,686
<i>Time to munch</i>
<i>an early luncheon</i>

79
00:06:35,762 --> 00:06:38,492
<i>Hum de dum dum dum</i>

80
00:06:38,564 --> 00:06:41,658
<i>Oh, I wouldn't climb this tree</i>

81
00:06:41,734 --> 00:06:44,328
<i>If a pooh flew like a bee</i>

82
00:06:44,404 --> 00:06:47,669
<i>But I wouldn't be a bear then</i>

83
00:06:47,740 --> 00:06:50,675
<i>So I guess</i>
<i>I wouldn't care then</i>

84
00:06:50,743 --> 00:06:54,509
<i>Bears love honey</i>
<i>and I'm a Pooh bear</i>

85
00:06:54,580 --> 00:06:57,447
<i>So I do care</i>
<i>So I climb there</i>

86
00:06:57,517 --> 00:07:00,680
<i>I'm so rumbly in my tumbly</i>

87
00:07:00,753 --> 00:07:02,618
<i>Time for something</i>

88
00:07:02,688 --> 00:07:07,853
For something sweet to eat!

89
00:07:07,927 --> 00:07:12,864
If only I hadn't...
You see, what I meant to do...

90
00:07:12,932 --> 00:07:16,800
And it all comes, I suppose,
from liking honey so much.

91
00:07:19,872 --> 00:07:22,340
Oh, bother.

92
00:07:22,408 --> 00:07:26,208
Winnie the Pooh
crawled out of the gorse bush...

93
00:07:26,279 --> 00:07:30,238
brushed the prickles from his nose
and began to think again.

94
00:07:30,316 --> 00:07:33,376
- Think, think, think.
- And the first person
he thought of was...

95
00:07:33,453 --> 00:07:36,581
- Winnie the Pooh?
- No. Christopher Robin.

96
00:07:36,656 --> 00:07:38,624
Oh.

97
00:07:38,758 --> 00:07:42,319
Christopher Robin lived
in another part of the forest...

98
00:07:42,395 --> 00:07:46,729
where he could be near his friends
and help them with their problems.

99
00:07:46,799 --> 00:07:50,360
On this summer day,
gloomy old Eeyore...

100
00:07:50,436 --> 00:07:54,896
being stuffed with sawdust,
had lost his tail again.

101
00:07:54,974 --> 00:07:58,740
- Eeyore, this won't hurt.
- Never does.

102
00:08:02,748 --> 00:08:06,081
There now. Did I get your tail
back on properly, Eeyore?

103
00:08:06,152 --> 00:08:10,350
No matter. Most likely
lose it again anyway.

104
00:08:12,358 --> 00:08:14,121
It is my considered opinion...

105
00:08:14,193 --> 00:08:18,562
that Eeyore's tail should be
placed a trifle to the, uh, right.

106
00:08:18,631 --> 00:08:23,364
And now, if you were to ask me,
I think it's just a wee bit...

107
00:08:23,436 --> 00:08:25,028
South.

108
00:08:25,104 --> 00:08:28,562
No, no. North, dear.

109
00:08:28,641 --> 00:08:33,635
Cheer up, Eeyore. Don't be so gloomy.
Try swishing it.

110
00:08:39,352 --> 00:08:42,412
- It worked. It worked.
- Oh, goody! Hooray!

111
00:08:42,488 --> 00:08:48,757
Thanks. It's not much of a tail,
but I'm sort of attached to it.

112
00:08:48,828 --> 00:08:53,731
- Good morning, Christopher Robin.
- Oh, good morning, Winnie the Pooh.

113
00:08:53,799 --> 00:08:56,233
- Good morning, Pooh bear.
- Good morning, Pooh bear.

114
00:08:56,302 --> 00:08:58,827
If it is a good morning,
which I doubt.

115
00:09:02,375 --> 00:09:08,075
- What are you looking for, Pooh bear?
- I just said to myself, coming along
thinking and wondering...

116
00:09:08,147 --> 00:09:10,775
if you had such a thing as, uh...

117
00:09:10,850 --> 00:09:15,116
such a thing, Christopher,
uh, as a balloon, about you.

118
00:09:17,490 --> 00:09:19,617
What do you want a balloon for?

119
00:09:23,162 --> 00:09:26,689
- Honey.
- But you don't get honey
with a balloon.

120
00:09:26,766 --> 00:09:29,758
- I do.
- How?

121
00:09:29,835 --> 00:09:34,272
I shall fly like a bee,
up to the honey tree. See?

122
00:09:34,340 --> 00:09:38,504
But just a minute.
You can't fool the bees that way.

123
00:09:38,578 --> 00:09:40,637
You'll see.

124
00:09:40,713 --> 00:09:46,345
Now, would you be so kind as to tow me
to a muddy place of which I know of.

125
00:09:46,419 --> 00:09:51,356
So Christopher Robin towed Winnie
the Pooh to the very muddy place.

126
00:09:53,793 --> 00:09:58,662
And Pooh rolled and rolled
until he was black all over.

127
00:10:02,435 --> 00:10:05,632
There, now.

128
00:10:05,705 --> 00:10:10,699
- Isn't this a clever disguise?
- What are you supposed to be?

129
00:10:12,878 --> 00:10:15,711
I'm a little, black
rain cloud, of course.

130
00:10:16,782 --> 00:10:18,647
Silly old bear.

131
00:10:18,718 --> 00:10:22,313
Now, would you aim me
at the bees, please?

132
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:28,349
- Careful, Pooh. Hold on tight.
- Yes.

133
00:10:28,427 --> 00:10:30,827
- Four...
- Yes.
- Three...
- Yes.

134
00:10:30,896 --> 00:10:33,592
- Two...
- Yes.
- One!

135
00:10:33,666 --> 00:10:38,262
<i>I'm just a little, black rain cloud</i>

136
00:10:38,337 --> 00:10:42,000
<i>Hovering under the honey tree</i>

137
00:10:42,074 --> 00:10:46,374
<i>I'm only a little, black rain cloud</i>

138
00:10:46,445 --> 00:10:49,608
<i>Pay no attention to little me</i>

139
00:10:49,682 --> 00:10:54,346
<i>Oh, everyone knows</i>
<i>that a rain cloud</i>

140
00:10:54,420 --> 00:10:57,287
<i>Never eats honey</i>
<i>no, not a nip</i>

141
00:10:57,356 --> 00:11:02,521
<i>I'm just floating around</i>
<i>over the ground</i>

142
00:11:02,595 --> 00:11:05,564
<i>Wondering where I will drip</i>

143
00:11:09,368 --> 00:11:13,532
Christopher Robin,
I think the bees...

144
00:11:13,606 --> 00:11:17,303
S-U-S-P-E-C-T something.

145
00:11:17,376 --> 00:11:19,867
Perhaps they think
you're after their honey.

146
00:11:19,945 --> 00:11:23,642
Well, it may be that.
You never can tell with bees.

147
00:11:23,716 --> 00:11:28,619
<i>Oh, I'm just</i>
<i>a little, black rain cloud</i>

148
00:11:28,688 --> 00:11:33,625
<i>Hovering under the honey tree</i>

149
00:12:06,659 --> 00:12:10,527
Christopher Robin!

150
00:12:10,596 --> 00:12:13,690
I think it would help
with this deception...

151
00:12:13,766 --> 00:12:17,258
if you would just kind of open
your umbrella and say...

152
00:12:17,336 --> 00:12:21,796
- "Tut, tut, it looks like rain."
- Tut, tut, it looks like rain.

153
00:12:21,874 --> 00:12:25,002
Tut, tut, it looks like rain.

154
00:12:37,223 --> 00:12:40,954
Christopher Robin, I have come
to a very important decision.

155
00:12:41,026 --> 00:12:45,019
These are the wrong sorts of bees.

156
00:13:01,447 --> 00:13:04,678
Excuse me, please, bees.

157
00:13:09,421 --> 00:13:12,015
Christopher Robin!

158
00:13:13,492 --> 00:13:16,188
Oh, bother!

159
00:13:16,262 --> 00:13:18,355
I think I shall come down.

160
00:13:19,431 --> 00:13:21,422
L'll catch you, Pooh.

161
00:13:26,605 --> 00:13:29,039
Hurry, come on. The bees!

162
00:13:30,943 --> 00:13:33,207
Help, Christopher!

163
00:13:39,852 --> 00:13:43,913
Christopher Robin,
you never can tell with bees.

164
00:13:48,360 --> 00:13:51,124
Now, Pooh was not the sort
to give up easily.

165
00:13:51,197 --> 00:13:55,224
When he put his mind to honey,
he stuck to it.

166
00:13:55,301 --> 00:13:58,236
Now, honey rhymes with bunny...

167
00:13:58,304 --> 00:14:00,465
and bunny rhymes with, uh...

168
00:14:00,539 --> 00:14:03,099
Rabbit?

169
00:14:03,175 --> 00:14:07,202
Yeah, I like Rabbit
because he uses short, easy words...

170
00:14:07,279 --> 00:14:11,875
like, "How about lunch"
and "Help yourself, Pooh."

171
00:14:11,951 --> 00:14:14,886
Pooh? Lunch?
Oh, no. Not again.

172
00:14:14,954 --> 00:14:17,650
Oh, my. Oh, my.
Oh, my goodness gracious!

173
00:14:17,723 --> 00:14:20,886
Is anybody at home?

174
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:24,919
What I said was,
"Is anybody at home?"

175
00:14:24,997 --> 00:14:27,795
- No.
- Bother.

176
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:31,633
- Isn't there anybody here at all?
- Nobody.

177
00:14:31,704 --> 00:14:37,438
Must be somebody there because
somebody must have said, "Nobody."

178
00:14:37,509 --> 00:14:39,841
- Rabbit, isn't that you?
- No!

179
00:14:39,912 --> 00:14:41,937
Well, isn't that the Rabbit's voice?

180
00:14:42,014 --> 00:14:46,178
I don't think so.
It isn't meant to be.

181
00:14:46,252 --> 00:14:48,277
- Hello, Rabbit.
- Oh.

182
00:14:48,354 --> 00:14:51,517
Oh, hello, Pooh bear.
Pooh bear!

183
00:14:51,590 --> 00:14:56,425
Uh, uh...
What a pleasant surprise.

184
00:14:56,495 --> 00:14:58,656
Uh, how about lunch?

185
00:14:58,731 --> 00:15:00,961
Oh, thank you, Rabbit.

186
00:15:01,033 --> 00:15:03,194
And help yourself, Pooh.

187
00:15:06,705 --> 00:15:11,665
Uh, would you like condensed milk
or honey on your bread?

188
00:15:11,744 --> 00:15:17,046
Both. But never mind the bread, please.
Just a small helping, if you please.

189
00:15:17,116 --> 00:15:19,846
Huh, there you are.

190
00:15:24,056 --> 00:15:26,183
Is, uh, something wrong?

191
00:15:26,258 --> 00:15:29,625
Well, I did mean
a little larger "small helping."

192
00:15:29,695 --> 00:15:32,789
Perhaps it would save time
if you took the whole jar.

193
00:15:32,865 --> 00:15:34,856
Thank you, Rabbit.

194
00:15:36,735 --> 00:15:41,001
So Pooh ate and ate
and ate and ate...

195
00:15:41,073 --> 00:15:43,837
and ate and ate
and ate and ate...

196
00:15:43,909 --> 00:15:45,900
and ate.

197
00:15:45,978 --> 00:15:48,208
Until at last he said to Rabbit...

198
00:15:48,280 --> 00:15:50,874
in a rather sticky voice:

199
00:15:50,950 --> 00:15:53,009
I must be going now.

200
00:15:53,085 --> 00:15:55,349
Good-bye, Rabbit.

201
00:15:55,421 --> 00:15:59,221
Well, good-bye, if you're sure
you won't have any more.

202
00:15:59,291 --> 00:16:03,387
- Is there any more?
- No, there isn't.

203
00:16:03,462 --> 00:16:05,487
I thought not.

204
00:16:10,469 --> 00:16:14,530
Oh, oh, help and bother!
I'm stuck.

205
00:16:14,606 --> 00:16:18,167
Oh, dear. Oh, gracious. Oh.

206
00:16:18,243 --> 00:16:20,768
Well, it all comes
from eating too much.

207
00:16:22,614 --> 00:16:26,573
It all comes from not having
front doors big enough!

208
00:16:28,787 --> 00:16:30,778
Oh, dear, it's no use.

209
00:16:30,856 --> 00:16:34,292
There's only one thing to do.
L'll get Christopher Robin.

210
00:16:34,360 --> 00:16:38,558
Oh, dear. Oh, dear. Oh, dear.
Oh, my. Heavens to Betsy.

211
00:16:48,307 --> 00:16:52,403
- Well, if it isn't Pooh bear.
- Oh, hello, Owl.

212
00:16:52,478 --> 00:16:56,107
Splendid day to be up and about
one's business, quite, eh?

213
00:16:58,117 --> 00:17:00,108
Oh.

214
00:17:01,687 --> 00:17:04,656
I say, are you stuck?

215
00:17:04,723 --> 00:17:07,817
No, no, just resting...

216
00:17:07,893 --> 00:17:11,989
and thinking
and humming to myself.

217
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:15,592
You, sir, are stuck...

218
00:17:15,667 --> 00:17:17,828
a wedged bear,
in a great tightness.

219
00:17:17,903 --> 00:17:20,497
In a word, irremovable.

220
00:17:20,572 --> 00:17:24,599
Now obviously, this situation
calls for an expert.

221
00:17:26,311 --> 00:17:29,803
Somebody call
for an excavation expert?

222
00:17:29,882 --> 00:17:32,442
I'm not in the book,
but I'm at your service.

223
00:17:32,518 --> 00:17:34,645
Gopher's the name.
Here's my card.

224
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:38,315
- What's your problem?
- Yes, yes, yes, yes.

225
00:17:38,390 --> 00:17:42,349
It seems the entrance
to Rabbit's domicile is impassable.

226
00:17:42,428 --> 00:17:44,988
Uh, to be exact, plugged.

227
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:47,123
And you want me to dig it out?

228
00:17:47,199 --> 00:17:49,497
Precisely.

229
00:17:49,568 --> 00:17:53,368
Uh, I say, it's over here,
my good fellow.

230
00:17:56,442 --> 00:17:59,934
Oh, the first thing to be done
is get rid of that bear.

231
00:18:00,012 --> 00:18:02,344
He's gummin' up the whole project.

232
00:18:02,414 --> 00:18:05,008
Dash it all, he is the project!

233
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:07,985
Um, hard digging.
Might hit bedrock.

234
00:18:08,053 --> 00:18:11,545
Danger of cave-in. Risky.

235
00:18:11,623 --> 00:18:16,356
Need planks for bracing.
Big job. Take two, three days.

236
00:18:16,428 --> 00:18:19,488
Three days?
What about lunches?

237
00:18:19,565 --> 00:18:23,365
No problem, I always go home for lunch.
Oh, oh! This will run into money.

238
00:18:23,435 --> 00:18:26,529
I, uh... I say, how much?

239
00:18:26,605 --> 00:18:31,065
Do the job for hourly rate
plus cover materials, plus overtime...

240
00:18:31,143 --> 00:18:33,373
plus ten percent.

241
00:18:33,445 --> 00:18:36,881
- And your estimate?
- Nope, can't give an estimate.

242
00:18:36,949 --> 00:18:40,043
- Too risky.
- Blast it all.

243
00:18:40,119 --> 00:18:44,419
- Good idea! We'll dynamite. Save time.
- Eh, what's the charge?

244
00:18:44,490 --> 00:18:47,254
The charge? Oh, about
seven sticks of dynamite.

245
00:18:47,326 --> 00:18:50,056
Oh, no, no, no, the cost!
The charge in money?

246
00:18:50,129 --> 00:18:53,189
Nope, no charge account.
I work strictly cash.

247
00:18:53,265 --> 00:18:55,529
Obviously, but, I should think...

248
00:18:55,601 --> 00:19:01,062
Well, I can't stand around lollygagging
all day. I got a tight schedule.

249
00:19:01,140 --> 00:19:05,099
If you think it over,
let me know. You got my card.
I'm not in the book, you know.

250
00:19:05,177 --> 00:19:08,704
Oh. Dash it all, he's gone.

251
00:19:08,780 --> 00:19:12,113
After all,
he's not in the book, you know.

252
00:19:12,184 --> 00:19:14,243
- Oh.
- Here we come. Don't worry.

253
00:19:14,920 --> 00:19:18,720
Cheer up, Pooh bear.
We're coming.

254
00:19:18,790 --> 00:19:22,123
- We'll get you out.
- Well, maybe.

255
00:19:22,194 --> 00:19:26,187
Silly old bear.
Here, give me your paw.

256
00:19:29,868 --> 00:19:33,235
Ow. It's no use. I'm stuck.

257
00:19:33,305 --> 00:19:37,469
Well, if we can't pull you out, Pooh,
perhaps we can push you back.

258
00:19:37,543 --> 00:19:40,307
Oh, no! Not that!
Oh, my gracious!

259
00:19:40,379 --> 00:19:42,904
Oh, dear!

260
00:19:42,981 --> 00:19:48,044
Having got this far,
it seems a pity to waste it.

261
00:19:48,120 --> 00:19:51,317
Pooh bear, there's only
one thing we can do:

262
00:19:51,390 --> 00:19:56,418
- Wait for you to get thin again.
- Oh, bother. How long will that take?

263
00:19:56,495 --> 00:20:00,659
Days. Weeks. Months.
Who knows?

264
00:20:00,732 --> 00:20:03,292
Oh, dear.

265
00:20:03,368 --> 00:20:06,269
If I have to face that...

266
00:20:06,338 --> 00:20:08,465
that thing for months...

267
00:20:08,540 --> 00:20:11,600
well, I might as well
make the best of it.

268
00:20:12,844 --> 00:20:15,813
Oh, no!
There it is again!

269
00:20:15,881 --> 00:20:19,578
Well, l'll just turn it to the wall.

270
00:20:19,651 --> 00:20:21,642
Oh, dear!

271
00:20:22,888 --> 00:20:25,584
Yes, a frame. Uh-huh.

272
00:20:28,727 --> 00:20:32,185
Oh. No, no, no. No.

273
00:20:33,932 --> 00:20:35,957
Very nice.

274
00:20:38,203 --> 00:20:41,036
And a splash of color.

275
00:20:41,106 --> 00:20:45,304
Oh, it just doesn't have
that rustic, informal look.

276
00:20:47,713 --> 00:20:50,773
There, a hunting trophy.

277
00:20:50,849 --> 00:20:53,841
Aha! I know just the thing.

278
00:20:54,920 --> 00:20:57,013
Something tickles.

279
00:20:59,391 --> 00:21:03,020
Oh, Pooh!
You messed up my moose!

280
00:21:04,429 --> 00:21:08,195
Pooh, Roo has a little surprise for you.

281
00:21:08,267 --> 00:21:12,328
- Flowers.
- Honeysuckle.

282
00:21:12,404 --> 00:21:17,398
No, Pooh, you don't eat them.
You smell them.

283
00:21:17,476 --> 00:21:19,876
Oh.

284
00:21:19,945 --> 00:21:24,348
That's not bad. Not bad at all.
It's rather good, I think.

285
00:21:24,416 --> 00:21:27,476
- Ah...
- Oh, no! Hold it!

286
00:21:28,820 --> 00:21:31,550
Oh, no! No, help!

287
00:21:33,392 --> 00:21:36,919
Why did I ever invite
that bear to lunch?

288
00:21:36,995 --> 00:21:40,089
Why, oh, why, oh, why?

289
00:21:40,165 --> 00:21:44,329
While Pooh's bottom was stuck
at the top of page 28...

290
00:21:44,403 --> 00:21:47,998
his top was stuck
at the bottom of page 30.

291
00:21:48,073 --> 00:21:51,167
So both ends waited
to get thin again...

292
00:21:51,243 --> 00:21:53,234
day after day...

293
00:21:53,312 --> 00:21:56,839
night after lonely night.

294
00:21:59,084 --> 00:22:02,850
I wonder what's for breakfast.

295
00:22:05,424 --> 00:22:07,619
Breakfast.

296
00:22:11,830 --> 00:22:13,855
Lunch.

297
00:22:13,932 --> 00:22:16,765
Huh? A lunch box!

298
00:22:16,835 --> 00:22:19,395
It certainly is!

299
00:22:19,471 --> 00:22:24,238
I'm working the swing shift, you know.
Time for my midnight snack.

300
00:22:24,309 --> 00:22:27,472
Say, ain't you that stuck-up bear?

301
00:22:27,546 --> 00:22:31,141
Hmm. I still think I could
blast you out of there.

302
00:22:31,216 --> 00:22:36,813
Uh, what sort of lunch
is in that lunch box?

303
00:22:36,888 --> 00:22:40,949
Well, let's see here.
Ah, um, oh!

304
00:22:41,026 --> 00:22:43,256
Summer squash...

305
00:22:45,230 --> 00:22:50,167
salmon salad, succotash,
spiced custard...

306
00:22:50,235 --> 00:22:52,260
and honey.

307
00:22:52,337 --> 00:22:56,171
- Honey?
- Honey? Oh, no!

308
00:22:57,542 --> 00:23:01,672
Could you spare
a small smackerel?

309
00:23:01,747 --> 00:23:05,979
Say, you ought to do something
about that speech impediment, sonny.

310
00:23:06,051 --> 00:23:08,645
- Oh, thank you, Gopher.
- Oh, no! Not that!

311
00:23:08,720 --> 00:23:11,985
No, no, no, no, no!
Not one drop!

312
00:23:12,057 --> 00:23:15,117
But, Rabbit,
I wasn't going to eat it.

313
00:23:15,193 --> 00:23:17,627
I was just going to taste it.

314
00:23:17,696 --> 00:23:19,960
L'll taste it for you.

315
00:23:20,031 --> 00:23:25,333
That supercilious scoundrel
confiscated my honey.

316
00:23:25,404 --> 00:23:28,498
Don't feed the bear.

317
00:23:30,208 --> 00:23:32,301
I'm going to skedaddle.

318
00:23:32,377 --> 00:23:35,107
I'm not in the book.

319
00:23:35,180 --> 00:23:37,205
And I'm "ding danged" glad of it!

320
00:23:38,083 --> 00:23:42,816
And then one morning
when Rabbit was beginning to think...

321
00:23:42,888 --> 00:23:46,847
that he might never be able to use
his front door again, it happened.

322
00:23:46,925 --> 00:23:49,621
He budged. Hooray!
"Christopher Crobbin."

323
00:23:49,694 --> 00:23:53,994
No, "Chrostofer Rubin."
He "bidged!" He "badged!" He "booged!"

324
00:23:54,065 --> 00:23:57,899
- Today is the day!
- <i>Hooray for you</i>

325
00:23:57,969 --> 00:24:00,130
<i>Hooray for me</i>

326
00:24:00,205 --> 00:24:04,835
<i>Hooray, hooray</i>
<i>The pooh will soon be free</i>

327
00:24:04,910 --> 00:24:08,539
<i>Dum ba dum</i>
<i>ba dum ba dum ba dum</i>

328
00:24:08,613 --> 00:24:10,979
<i>Now the time has</i>
<i>come for proving</i>

329
00:24:11,049 --> 00:24:13,142
<i>What the diet did for Pooh</i>

330
00:24:13,218 --> 00:24:15,345
<i>And since we pledged</i>
<i>he'd be unwedged</i>

331
00:24:15,420 --> 00:24:17,411
<i>That's what we're going to do</i>

332
00:24:17,489 --> 00:24:19,753
<i>He'll be pulled</i>
<i>and he'll be tugged</i>

333
00:24:19,825 --> 00:24:21,850
<i>And eventually unplugged</i>

334
00:24:21,927 --> 00:24:24,157
<i>We'll have a tug-of-war</i>

335
00:24:24,229 --> 00:24:27,198
<i>To open Rabbit's door</i>

336
00:24:27,265 --> 00:24:32,032
<i>Think "heave-age,"think "ho-age"</i>

337
00:24:32,103 --> 00:24:36,733
<i>And out the pooh will "go-age"</i>

338
00:24:36,808 --> 00:24:41,370
<i>For mind over matter</i>

339
00:24:41,446 --> 00:24:45,712
<i>Has made the pooh "un-fatter"</i>

340
00:24:48,787 --> 00:24:51,119
<i>Heave-ho</i>

341
00:24:51,189 --> 00:24:53,123
<i>Heave-ho</i>

342
00:24:53,191 --> 00:24:58,561
<i>Heave, heave, heave, heave, heave</i>

343
00:24:59,998 --> 00:25:02,796
- There he goes!
- Suffering sassafras.

344
00:25:02,868 --> 00:25:08,033
He's sailing clean out of the book!
Quick! Turn the page!

345
00:25:14,279 --> 00:25:16,270
Stuck again.

346
00:25:16,348 --> 00:25:18,873
Don't worry, Pooh.
We'll get you out.

347
00:25:18,950 --> 00:25:22,249
No hurry. Take your time.

348
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:24,413
Yum-yum.

349
00:25:25,724 --> 00:25:28,318
<i>Bears love honey</i>
<i>and I'm a pooh bear</i>

350
00:25:28,393 --> 00:25:32,329
<i>Yum, yum, yum, yum</i>
<i>Slurp, slurp, slurp, slurp</i>

351
00:25:32,397 --> 00:25:36,595
<i>Yum, yum, yum, yum</i>
<i>Time for something sweet</i>

352
00:25:36,668 --> 00:25:39,262
And so we come
to the next chapter in which...

353
00:25:39,337 --> 00:25:41,737
But I haven't finished yet.

354
00:25:41,806 --> 00:25:44,104
But, Pooh, you're in the next chapter.

355
00:25:44,175 --> 00:25:47,076
Oh. What happens to me?

356
00:25:47,145 --> 00:25:50,512
Well, let's turn the page
and find out.

357
00:25:50,649 --> 00:25:53,846
Now, one fine day, the east wind...

358
00:25:53,919 --> 00:25:56,353
traded places with the west wind.

359
00:25:56,421 --> 00:26:00,983
And that stirred things up a bit
all through the Hundred-Acre Wood.

360
00:26:05,664 --> 00:26:07,655
Now, on this blustery day...

361
00:26:07,732 --> 00:26:11,168
Pooh decided to visit
his thoughtful spot.

362
00:26:11,236 --> 00:26:14,171
Yes, and on the way
I made up a little hum.

363
00:26:14,239 --> 00:26:17,436
And it hums something like this.

364
00:26:17,509 --> 00:26:21,605
<i>Hum dum, dum ditty dum</i>
<i>Hum dum, dum</i>

365
00:26:21,680 --> 00:26:26,208
<i>Oh, the wind is lashing lustily</i>
<i>and the trees are thrashing thrustily</i>

366
00:26:26,284 --> 00:26:28,548
<i>And the leaves are rustling gustily</i>

367
00:26:28,620 --> 00:26:30,884
<i>So it's rather safe to say</i>

368
00:26:30,956 --> 00:26:34,517
<i>That it seems that</i>
<i>it may turn out to be</i>

369
00:26:36,027 --> 00:26:38,359
<i>It feels that it will undoubtedly</i>

370
00:26:40,432 --> 00:26:44,459
<i>It looks like a rather</i>
<i>blustery day today</i>

371
00:26:44,536 --> 00:26:47,801
<i>It seems that</i>
<i>it may turn out to be</i>

372
00:26:47,872 --> 00:26:49,897
<i>Feels that it will undoubtedly</i>

373
00:26:49,975 --> 00:26:54,571
<i>Looks like a rather blustery day today</i>

374
00:26:56,715 --> 00:27:00,742
Fortunately, Pooh's thoughtful spot
was in a sheltered place.

375
00:27:00,819 --> 00:27:04,380
Now he sat down and tried
hard to think of something.

376
00:27:04,456 --> 00:27:06,981
Think, think, think, think, think.

377
00:27:10,261 --> 00:27:12,923
Think, think, think.

378
00:27:12,998 --> 00:27:17,731
Say, what's wrong, sonny?
Got yourself a headache?

379
00:27:17,802 --> 00:27:22,501
- No, I was just thinking.
- Is that so? What about?

380
00:27:22,574 --> 00:27:26,237
L... Oh, bother.
You made me forget.

381
00:27:26,311 --> 00:27:30,338
If I was you, I'd think about
skedaddling out of here.

382
00:27:30,415 --> 00:27:33,782
- Why?
- 'Cause it's "Winds-day."

383
00:27:33,852 --> 00:27:38,448
"Winds-day"? Oh!

384
00:27:38,523 --> 00:27:41,458
Then I think I shall wish
everyone a happy "Winds-day"...

385
00:27:41,526 --> 00:27:46,623
and I shall begin with
my very dear friend, Piglet.

386
00:27:46,698 --> 00:27:51,431
Now, Piglet lived in the middle
of the forest in a very grand house...

387
00:27:51,503 --> 00:27:53,528
in the middle of a beech tree.

388
00:27:53,605 --> 00:27:56,472
And Piglet loved it very much.

389
00:27:56,541 --> 00:27:59,533
Whew, yes.

390
00:27:59,611 --> 00:28:03,809
Whoops. You see, it's been
in the family a long time.

391
00:28:03,882 --> 00:28:06,646
It belonged to my grandfather.

392
00:28:06,718 --> 00:28:11,314
Oh, that's his name up there,
"Trespassers Will."

393
00:28:11,389 --> 00:28:13,789
That's short for "Trespassers William."

394
00:28:13,858 --> 00:28:17,055
- Trespassers William?
- Yes.

395
00:28:17,128 --> 00:28:19,722
And Grandma... Oh.

396
00:28:19,798 --> 00:28:22,289
She called him T.W.

397
00:28:22,367 --> 00:28:25,063
That's even shorter.

398
00:28:25,136 --> 00:28:27,263
Yes, yes, yes.

399
00:28:27,338 --> 00:28:29,602
- And on this blustery day...
- Whoo!

400
00:28:29,674 --> 00:28:31,733
The wind was giving you
a bit of a bother.

401
00:28:31,810 --> 00:28:34,779
Now, you've been here before.

402
00:28:34,846 --> 00:28:36,837
I don't mind the leaves
that are leaving.

403
00:28:36,915 --> 00:28:40,817
It's the leaves that are coming.
Whoops!

404
00:28:40,885 --> 00:28:46,983
- Happy "Winds-day," Piglet.
- Well, it isn't very happy for me.

405
00:28:47,058 --> 00:28:51,927
- Where are you going, Piglet?
- That's what I'm asking myself, where?

406
00:28:51,996 --> 00:28:55,022
W-Whoops! P-P-Pooh!

407
00:28:55,100 --> 00:28:57,466
And what do you think
you will answer yourself?

408
00:28:57,535 --> 00:28:59,935
Oh, oh, oh! I'm unravelling.

409
00:29:03,241 --> 00:29:07,678
Whoops!
Oh, t-t-that was a c-c-close one!

410
00:29:07,746 --> 00:29:10,681
Hang on tight, Piglet.

411
00:29:10,749 --> 00:29:13,343
Oh, dear.
Oh, d-d-dear, dear!

412
00:29:17,455 --> 00:29:20,686
Look, Mama, look! A kite!

413
00:29:20,759 --> 00:29:23,489
Oh, my goodness, it's Piglet!

414
00:29:23,561 --> 00:29:27,053
Happy "Winds-day," Kanga.
Happy "Winds-day," Roo.

415
00:29:27,132 --> 00:29:29,498
Can I fly Piglet next, Pooh?

416
00:29:29,567 --> 00:29:31,865
Oh, dear.
Oh, d-d-dear, dear!

417
00:29:33,304 --> 00:29:36,137
There, that should
stand against anything.

418
00:29:36,207 --> 00:29:41,509
Oh, oh! Help, help!
Somebody, s-s-save me!

419
00:29:41,579 --> 00:29:46,676
- Happy "Winds-day," Eeyore.
- Thanks for noticing me.

420
00:29:46,751 --> 00:29:49,151
Oh, b-b-b-bother!

421
00:29:49,220 --> 00:29:54,157
Ah. Oh, what a refreshing
day for harvesting.

422
00:29:54,225 --> 00:29:59,663
- Happy Winds-day, Rabbit.
- Pooh bear, Stop! Oh, go back! Oh, no!

423
00:29:59,731 --> 00:30:02,325
Oh, no! Oh, no!

424
00:30:02,400 --> 00:30:04,425
Oh, yes!

425
00:30:04,502 --> 00:30:08,097
Well, next time, I hope he blows
right through my rutabaga patch.

426
00:30:19,484 --> 00:30:22,885
- Whoops!
- Huh? Who, who, who? Who is it?

427
00:30:22,954 --> 00:30:26,788
It's me.
P-P-Please, may I come in?

428
00:30:26,858 --> 00:30:29,088
Well, I say now.

429
00:30:29,160 --> 00:30:33,426
Someone has pasted
Piglet on my window.

430
00:30:33,498 --> 00:30:35,591
Well, well! Pooh too.

431
00:30:35,667 --> 00:30:38,932
This is a surprise.

432
00:30:39,003 --> 00:30:41,130
Do come in and make yourselves...

433
00:30:43,041 --> 00:30:47,102
- comfortable.
- Oh!

434
00:30:47,178 --> 00:30:52,275
Am I correct in assuming it is
a rather blustery day outside?

435
00:30:52,350 --> 00:30:55,979
Yes, sir, Owl. It's a very,
very blustery day outside.

436
00:30:56,054 --> 00:30:58,648
Oh, yes. That reminds me.

437
00:30:58,723 --> 00:31:01,920
Happy "Winds-day," Owl.

438
00:31:01,993 --> 00:31:06,896
My good fellow, I wouldn't go
so far as to call it a "Winds-day"...

439
00:31:06,965 --> 00:31:08,990
just a gentle spring zephyr.

440
00:31:09,067 --> 00:31:12,298
Excuse me, Owl, but...

441
00:31:12,370 --> 00:31:14,668
is there honey in that pot?

442
00:31:14,739 --> 00:31:18,607
Oh, yes, yes, of course. Help yourself.
Now, as I was saying...

443
00:31:18,676 --> 00:31:23,010
this is just a mild spring zephyr
compared to the big wind of'67.

444
00:31:23,081 --> 00:31:26,778
Or was it, uh, '76?
Oh, well, no matter.

445
00:31:26,851 --> 00:31:31,914
- Oh, I remember the big blow well.
- L'll remember this one too.

446
00:31:31,990 --> 00:31:35,949
It was the year my Aunt Clara
went to visit her cousin.

447
00:31:36,027 --> 00:31:39,519
Now, her cousin was not only
gifted on the glockenspiel...

448
00:31:39,597 --> 00:31:44,694
but being a screech owl, also sang
soprano in the London opera.

449
00:31:47,171 --> 00:31:50,368
- Thank you, Piglet.
- You see, her constant practicing...

450
00:31:50,441 --> 00:31:55,469
so unnerved my aunt that
she laid a sea gull egg by mistake.

451
00:32:06,524 --> 00:32:08,685
Oh, dear.
Oh, d-d-dear, dear.

452
00:32:11,462 --> 00:32:16,126
Well, I say now, someone has...

453
00:32:16,200 --> 00:32:20,364
Pooh, did you do that?

454
00:32:20,438 --> 00:32:23,566
I don't think so.

455
00:32:23,641 --> 00:32:26,371
As soon as Christopher Robin
heard of the disaster...

456
00:32:26,444 --> 00:32:29,311
he hurried to the scene
of Owl's misfortune.

457
00:32:30,915 --> 00:32:32,974
What a pity.

458
00:32:33,051 --> 00:32:36,487
Owl, I don't think we will
ever be able to fix it.

459
00:32:36,554 --> 00:32:40,320
If you ask me,
when a house looks like that...

460
00:32:40,391 --> 00:32:44,384
- it's time to find another one.
- That's a very good idea, Eeyore.

461
00:32:44,462 --> 00:32:48,831
Might take a day or two,
but l'll find a new one.

462
00:32:48,900 --> 00:32:53,394
Good, that will just give me time
to tell you about my Uncle Clyde...

463
00:32:53,471 --> 00:32:55,496
a very independent barn owl.

464
00:32:55,573 --> 00:32:59,339
He didn't give a hoot for tradition.
He became enamored of a pussycat...

465
00:32:59,410 --> 00:33:02,345
and went to sea
in a beautiful pea-green boat.

466
00:33:03,581 --> 00:33:08,450
Owl talked from page 41 to page 62.

467
00:33:08,519 --> 00:33:14,719
And on page 62, the blustery day
turned into a blustery night.

468
00:33:14,792 --> 00:33:18,353
To Pooh, it was a very anxious
sort of night...

469
00:33:18,429 --> 00:33:21,921
filled with anxious sorts of noises.

470
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:27,700
And one of the noises was a sound
that had never been heard before.

471
00:33:30,108 --> 00:33:33,703
Ah, is that you, Piglet?

472
00:33:38,116 --> 00:33:42,314
W-Well, tell me about it
tomorrow, Eeyore?

473
00:33:44,355 --> 00:33:47,381
Oh, come in,
Christopher Robin.

474
00:33:49,460 --> 00:33:53,624
Now Pooh, being a bear
of very little brain...

475
00:33:53,698 --> 00:33:57,065
decided to invite
the new sound in.

476
00:34:03,174 --> 00:34:05,836
Hello, out there.

477
00:34:05,910 --> 00:34:08,674
Oh, I hope nobody answers.

478
00:34:10,081 --> 00:34:15,644
- Hello, I'm Tigger!
- Oh. You scared me.

479
00:34:15,720 --> 00:34:19,850
Yeah, sure I did.
Everyone's scared of tiggers.

480
00:34:19,924 --> 00:34:21,949
- Uh, who are you?
- I'm Pooh.

481
00:34:22,026 --> 00:34:25,325
Oh, a pooh. Sure.

482
00:34:25,396 --> 00:34:28,297
- What's a pooh?
- You're sitting on one.

483
00:34:28,366 --> 00:34:31,494
I am? Oh, well, glad to meet ya.
Name's Tigger.

484
00:34:31,569 --> 00:34:36,199
T-I, double "guh," "err."
That spells "Tigger."

485
00:34:36,274 --> 00:34:38,299
But what is a tigger?

486
00:34:38,376 --> 00:34:42,335
Well, he asked for it!

487
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:45,313
<i>The wonderful thing about tiggers</i>
<i>is tiggers are wonderful things</i>

488
00:34:45,383 --> 00:34:48,147
<i>Their tops are made out of rubber</i>
<i>Their bottoms are made out of springs</i>

489
00:34:48,219 --> 00:34:50,847
<i>They're bouncy, trouncy, flouncy</i>
<i>pouncy fun, fun, fun, fun, fun</i>

490
00:34:50,922 --> 00:34:53,857
<i>But the most wonderful thing</i>
<i>about tiggers is I'm the only one</i>

491
00:34:53,925 --> 00:34:57,292
<i>I'm the only one</i>

492
00:34:57,361 --> 00:35:01,730
- Then what's that over there?
- Huh? Oh, hey, hey. Look, look, look.

493
00:35:01,799 --> 00:35:05,860
Oh, what a strange-looking creature.

494
00:35:05,937 --> 00:35:11,204
Look at those beady little eyes,
and that "purrposturous" chin...

495
00:35:11,275 --> 00:35:15,644
and those "rickydiculus"
striped pajamas.

496
00:35:15,713 --> 00:35:21,913
- Looked like another tigger to me.
- Oh, no, it's not. I'm the only tigger.

497
00:35:21,986 --> 00:35:25,353
Watch me scare the stripes
off of this impostor.

498
00:35:30,394 --> 00:35:32,862
Is-Is-Is... Is he gone?

499
00:35:32,930 --> 00:35:36,559
All except the tail.
He's gone.

500
00:35:36,634 --> 00:35:40,229
Uh, you can come out now, Tigger.

501
00:35:40,304 --> 00:35:42,738
Tigger?

502
00:35:42,807 --> 00:35:46,538
- Hello, I'm Tigger.
- You said that.

503
00:35:46,611 --> 00:35:50,377
- Oh? Well, did I say I was hungry?
- I don't think so.

504
00:35:50,448 --> 00:35:53,440
Well, then l'll say it.
I'm hungry.

505
00:35:53,518 --> 00:35:55,543
Oh, not for honey, I hope.

506
00:35:55,620 --> 00:35:57,713
Honey! Oh, boy, honey!

507
00:35:57,788 --> 00:36:02,851
- That's what tiggers like best.
- I was afraid of that.

508
00:36:04,462 --> 00:36:06,453
Oh, say.

509
00:36:08,099 --> 00:36:12,536
Yuck! Tiggers don't like honey!

510
00:36:12,603 --> 00:36:18,405
- But you said that you liked...
- That icky, sticky stuff is only fit
for "heffalumps" and "woozles."

511
00:36:18,476 --> 00:36:20,467
You mean elephants and weasels.

512
00:36:20,545 --> 00:36:22,479
That's what I said...
"heffalumps" and "woozles."

513
00:36:22,547 --> 00:36:27,644
Well, what do heffa... lalla...
What do they do?

514
00:36:27,718 --> 00:36:31,154
- Oh, nothin' much. Just steal honey.
- Steal honey?

515
00:36:31,222 --> 00:36:36,455
Yeah, they sure do. Well, I'd better be
bouncing along now, chum. Cheerio!

516
00:36:36,527 --> 00:36:39,462
<i>The wonderful thing about tiggers</i>
<i>is tiggers are wonderful things</i>

517
00:36:39,530 --> 00:36:42,328
<i>Their tops are made out of rubber</i>
<i>their bottoms are made out of springs</i>

518
00:36:42,400 --> 00:36:45,130
