<i>They're quick and slick</i>
<i>They're insincere</i>

565
00:41:12,236 --> 00:41:15,831
<i>Beware, beware, beware, beware</i>

566
00:41:15,906 --> 00:41:19,239
<i>Beware</i>

567
00:41:28,118 --> 00:41:32,680
Is it raining in there?
It's raining out here too.

568
00:41:32,756 --> 00:41:36,920
As a matter of fact, it was raining
all over the Hundred-Acre Wood.

569
00:41:36,994 --> 00:41:40,862
There was a thunder storm
on page 71.

570
00:41:40,931 --> 00:41:45,732
And on page 73,
there was a bit of a cloudburst.

571
00:41:45,803 --> 00:41:50,137
It rained and it rained
and it rained.

572
00:41:50,207 --> 00:41:52,732
<i>The rain, rain, rain</i>
<i>came down, down, down</i>

573
00:41:52,810 --> 00:41:54,869
<i>In rushing rising rivulets</i>

574
00:41:54,945 --> 00:41:57,106
<i>Till the river crept out of its bed</i>

575
00:41:57,181 --> 00:41:59,376
<i>And crept right into Piglet's</i>

576
00:41:59,450 --> 00:42:01,441
<i>Poor Piglet he was frightened</i>

577
00:42:01,519 --> 00:42:04,113
<i>With quite a rightful fright</i>

578
00:42:04,188 --> 00:42:09,251
<i>And so in desperation</i>
<i>a message he did write</i>

579
00:42:10,661 --> 00:42:14,256
Help! P-P-Piglet... Me!

580
00:42:14,331 --> 00:42:17,664
<i>He placed it in a bottle</i>

581
00:42:17,735 --> 00:42:21,671
<i>And it floated out of sight</i>

582
00:42:21,739 --> 00:42:24,333
<i>And the rain, rain, rain</i>
<i>came down, down, down</i>

583
00:42:24,408 --> 00:42:26,808
<i>So Piglet started bailing</i>

584
00:42:31,649 --> 00:42:36,086
<i>He was unaware atop his chair</i>
<i>while bailing he was sailing</i>

585
00:42:36,153 --> 00:42:38,587
<i>And the rain, rain, rain</i>
<i>came down, down, down</i>

586
00:42:38,656 --> 00:42:40,647
<i>And the flood rose</i>
<i>up, up, upper</i>

587
00:42:40,724 --> 00:42:43,022
<i>Pooh too was caught</i>
<i>and so he thought</i>

588
00:42:43,093 --> 00:42:45,323
<i>I must rescue my supper</i>

589
00:42:45,396 --> 00:42:50,095
<i>Ten honey pots he rescued</i>
<i>enough to see him through</i>

590
00:42:50,167 --> 00:42:52,658
<i>But as he sopped up his supper</i>

591
00:42:52,736 --> 00:42:56,263
<i>The river sopped up Pooh</i>

592
00:42:57,575 --> 00:43:00,009
<i>And the water twirled</i>
<i>and tossed him</i>

593
00:43:00,077 --> 00:43:02,671
<i>In a honey pot canoe</i>

594
00:43:02,746 --> 00:43:04,839
<i>Rain, rain, rain</i>
<i>came down, down, down</i>

595
00:43:04,915 --> 00:43:07,179
<i>When the rain, rain, rain</i>
<i>came down, down, down</i>

596
00:43:07,251 --> 00:43:11,654
So the Hundred-Acre Wood
got floodier and floodier.

597
00:43:11,722 --> 00:43:14,691
But the water couldn't come up
to Christopher Robin's house...

598
00:43:14,758 --> 00:43:17,352
so that's where
everyone was gathering.

599
00:43:17,428 --> 00:43:20,022
It was a time of great excitement.

600
00:43:20,097 --> 00:43:22,156
But in the midst
of all the excitement...

601
00:43:22,232 --> 00:43:26,498
Eeyore stubbornly stuck to his task
of house-hunting for Owl.

602
00:43:26,570 --> 00:43:32,031
There's one.
Cozy cottage, nice location.

603
00:43:32,109 --> 00:43:35,169
A bit damp for Owl, though.

604
00:43:35,245 --> 00:43:38,578
Meanwhile, little Roo made
an important discovery.

605
00:43:38,649 --> 00:43:43,245
Look! I've rescued a bottle.
And it's got something in it too.

606
00:43:44,622 --> 00:43:46,817
It's a message, and it says:

607
00:43:46,890 --> 00:43:50,257
"Help! P-P-Piglet... Me!"

608
00:43:50,327 --> 00:43:53,387
Owl, you fly over to Piglet's house...

609
00:43:53,464 --> 00:43:55,728
and tell him we'll make a rescue.

610
00:43:55,799 --> 00:43:58,734
A rescue? Yes, yes.
Of course, of course.

611
00:44:00,137 --> 00:44:02,537
So Owl flew out over the flood...

612
00:44:02,606 --> 00:44:05,370
and he soon spotted
two tiny objects below him.

613
00:44:05,442 --> 00:44:09,378
One was little Piglet
caught in the whirlpool...

614
00:44:09,446 --> 00:44:13,280
and the other was Pooh trying to get
the last bit of honey from the pot.

615
00:44:13,350 --> 00:44:15,375
Yum-yum.

616
00:44:15,452 --> 00:44:20,389
Oh, Owl, I don't mean to c-c-complain,
but I'm afraid I'm scared.

617
00:44:20,457 --> 00:44:23,449
Now, now, Piglet, chin up
and all that sort of thing.

618
00:44:23,527 --> 00:44:27,554
A rescue is being thought of.
Be brave, little Piglet.

619
00:44:27,631 --> 00:44:31,567
It's awfully hard to be b-b-brave
when you're such a small animal.

620
00:44:31,635 --> 00:44:35,594
Then to divert your small mind
from your unfortunate predicament...

621
00:44:35,673 --> 00:44:39,302
I shall tell you
an amusing anecdote.

622
00:44:41,145 --> 00:44:43,613
It concerns a distant cousin of mine...

623
00:44:43,681 --> 00:44:46,081
who became so frightened
during a flood that he...

624
00:44:46,150 --> 00:44:48,414
I beg your pardon, Owl,
but I th-think...

625
00:44:48,485 --> 00:44:52,387
we're coming to a "flutterfall"...
a "flatterfall"...a very big waterfall.

626
00:44:52,456 --> 00:44:54,754
Please, no interruptions.

627
00:45:13,510 --> 00:45:17,412
Ah, there you are, Pooh bear.
Now, to continue my story...

628
00:45:17,481 --> 00:45:21,144
Look, there's Pooh.
Over here, Pooh!

629
00:45:21,218 --> 00:45:23,277
Oh, hello, Christopher Robin.

630
00:45:23,353 --> 00:45:27,790
Pooh, thank goodness you're safe.
Have you seen Piglet?

631
00:45:27,858 --> 00:45:30,019
Excuse me, I have...

632
00:45:30,094 --> 00:45:33,461
What I mean is, here I am.

633
00:45:33,530 --> 00:45:37,489
- Pooh, you rescued Piglet.
- I did?

634
00:45:37,568 --> 00:45:40,594
Yes, and it was
a very brave thing to do.

635
00:45:40,671 --> 00:45:42,263
It was?

636
00:45:42,339 --> 00:45:44,933
- You are our hero.
- I am?

637
00:45:45,008 --> 00:45:49,809
And as soon as the flood is over,
I shall give you a hero party.

638
00:45:54,852 --> 00:45:56,843
Attention, everybody.

639
00:45:56,920 --> 00:46:01,948
Now, this party is a hero party
because of what someone did.

640
00:46:02,025 --> 00:46:07,019
- And that someone is...
- I found it.

641
00:46:07,097 --> 00:46:10,794
- Found what, Eeyore?
- House for Owl.

642
00:46:10,868 --> 00:46:14,463
I say, Eeyore, good show!

643
00:46:14,538 --> 00:46:17,871
Oh, isn't that wonderful.
Where is it, Eeyore?

644
00:46:17,941 --> 00:46:21,707
If you want to follow me,
l'll show it to you.

645
00:46:23,113 --> 00:46:25,138
So everyone followed Eeyore.

646
00:46:25,215 --> 00:46:29,709
Then, to the surprise of all,
Eeyore stopped right in front of...

647
00:46:29,787 --> 00:46:32,153
Piglet's house?

648
00:46:32,222 --> 00:46:34,656
Why are you
stopping here, Eeyore?

649
00:46:34,725 --> 00:46:38,183
This is it, Owl's new house.

650
00:46:38,262 --> 00:46:40,355
Oh, dear, mercy me!

651
00:46:40,430 --> 00:46:43,024
Oh, dear, mercy me too!

652
00:46:43,100 --> 00:46:45,534
Name's on it and everything.

653
00:46:45,602 --> 00:46:49,868
W-O-L, that spells Owl.

654
00:46:49,940 --> 00:46:53,273
Bless my soul, so it does.

655
00:46:53,343 --> 00:46:55,709
Well, what do you think of it?

656
00:46:55,779 --> 00:47:00,546
It is a nice house, Eeyore, but...

657
00:47:00,617 --> 00:47:04,883
It is a lovely house, Eeyore, but...

658
00:47:04,955 --> 00:47:09,892
It's... It's the best house
in the whole world.

659
00:47:09,960 --> 00:47:12,292
Tell them it's your house, Piglet.

660
00:47:12,362 --> 00:47:14,421
No, Pooh.

661
00:47:14,498 --> 00:47:19,265
This house belongs
to our very good friend...

662
00:47:19,336 --> 00:47:22,032
Owl.

663
00:47:22,105 --> 00:47:24,972
But, Piglet, where will you live?

664
00:47:25,042 --> 00:47:28,034
Well, l...
I guess I shall live...

665
00:47:29,112 --> 00:47:31,307
I suppose l-I shall live...

666
00:47:31,381 --> 00:47:35,442
With me! You shall live with me.
Won't you, Piglet?

667
00:47:35,519 --> 00:47:37,885
With you?

668
00:47:37,955 --> 00:47:42,915
Oh, thank you, Pooh bear.
Of course I will.

669
00:47:42,993 --> 00:47:46,588
Piglet, that was a very
grand thing to do.

670
00:47:46,663 --> 00:47:49,427
A heroic thing to do.

671
00:47:49,499 --> 00:47:51,797
Christopher Robin...

672
00:47:51,869 --> 00:47:57,102
can you make a one-hero party
into a two-hero party?

673
00:47:57,174 --> 00:47:59,267
Of course we can...

674
00:47:59,343 --> 00:48:01,607
silly old bear.

675
00:48:01,678 --> 00:48:04,772
And so, Pooh was a hero
for saving Piglet...

676
00:48:04,848 --> 00:48:09,114
and Piglet was a hero for giving Owl
his grand home in the beech tree.

677
00:48:09,186 --> 00:48:13,282
<i>We never will forget</i>
<i>our hero of the wet</i>

678
00:48:13,357 --> 00:48:17,293
<i>Our quick thinking</i>
<i>unsinking Pooh bear</i>

679
00:48:17,361 --> 00:48:21,457
<i>And Piglet who indeed</i>
<i>helped out a friend in need</i>

680
00:48:21,531 --> 00:48:23,965
<i>Truly they're the heroes of the day</i>

681
00:48:24,034 --> 00:48:29,973
<i>So we say, Hip hip hooray</i>
<i>for the piglet and the pooh</i>

682
00:48:30,040 --> 00:48:35,444
- <i>Piglet and Pooh, we salute you</i>
- What's all that stompin' and singin'
and silly shenanigans?

683
00:48:35,512 --> 00:48:37,309
<i>And generosity</i>

684
00:48:37,381 --> 00:48:41,317
<i>Hip hip hooray</i>
<i>Hip hip hooray</i>

685
00:48:41,385 --> 00:48:44,877
<i>Hip hip hooray for Winnie the Pooh</i>

686
00:48:46,924 --> 00:48:48,983
And Piglet too!

687
00:48:49,059 --> 00:48:53,120
I sure like bouncing.
Wasn't that fun, Piglet?

688
00:48:53,196 --> 00:48:59,135
Yes, Pooh, b-but the best part
is when it st-stops.

689
00:48:59,202 --> 00:49:03,195
Well, in the next chapter,
there's a great deal of bouncing.

690
00:49:03,273 --> 00:49:06,140
There is? Oh.

691
00:49:06,209 --> 00:49:08,302
I think that I just remembered...

692
00:49:08,378 --> 00:49:10,471
something that
I forgot to do yesterday...

693
00:49:10,547 --> 00:49:13,209
and-and shan't be able
to do tomorrow.

694
00:49:13,283 --> 00:49:17,219
So I suppose I really ought to go back
and-and do it n-now.

695
00:49:17,287 --> 00:49:20,688
- Uh, good-bye, Pooh.
- Good-bye, Piglet.

696
00:49:20,757 --> 00:49:23,749
Now, is the next chapter all about me?

697
00:49:23,827 --> 00:49:28,855
- No, no. It's mostly about Tigger.
- Oh, bother.

698
00:49:28,932 --> 00:49:31,662
- But you're in it.
- Oh, good.

699
00:49:31,735 --> 00:49:33,726
What will I be doing?

700
00:49:33,870 --> 00:49:38,102
Well, Pooh, you'll be sitting
in your thoughtful spot...

701
00:49:38,175 --> 00:49:40,575
thinking, as usual.

702
00:49:40,606 --> 00:49:43,803
Think, think. Think, think, think.
Think. Think.

703
00:49:43,875 --> 00:49:46,537
And while he was thinking,
all of a sudden...

704
00:49:46,612 --> 00:49:49,843
Hello, Pooh!
I'm Tigger!

705
00:49:49,915 --> 00:49:53,476
T-I, double "guh," "err."
That spells "Tigger."

706
00:49:53,552 --> 00:49:56,180
Yeah, I know.

707
00:49:56,254 --> 00:50:00,213
- You've bounced me before.
- I did?

708
00:50:00,292 --> 00:50:04,854
Oh, yeah! I "recoggonize" you. You're
the one that's stuffed with fluff.

709
00:50:04,930 --> 00:50:09,560
- Yeah. And you're sitting on it.
- Yeah. And it's comfy too.

710
00:50:09,635 --> 00:50:13,366
Well, I gotta go now.
I got a lot of bouncing to do.

711
00:50:13,438 --> 00:50:15,770
T-T-F-N.
Ta-ta for now.

712
00:50:16,975 --> 00:50:19,205
Well, there goes Tigger...

713
00:50:19,277 --> 00:50:22,542
always bouncing in on his friends
when they least expect him.

714
00:50:24,349 --> 00:50:26,874
Oh, hello, Piglet!
I'm Tigger.

715
00:50:26,952 --> 00:50:29,546
Oh, Tigger.
You sc-scared me.

716
00:50:29,621 --> 00:50:31,714
Oh, shucks.

717
00:50:31,790 --> 00:50:33,883
That was just
one of my little bounces.

718
00:50:33,959 --> 00:50:36,894
It was?
Oh, thank you, Tigger.

719
00:50:36,962 --> 00:50:41,729
Yeah. I'm saving my best bounce
for old long-ears!

720
00:50:42,801 --> 00:50:44,462
Ta-ta!

721
00:50:44,536 --> 00:50:46,800
<i>Hum de dum, dum</i>
<i>Hum de dum, dum</i>

722
00:50:46,872 --> 00:50:49,432
<i>Hum de dum, dum</i>
<i>Dum de dum, dum</i>

723
00:50:49,508 --> 00:50:52,204
There. There. That should do it.

724
00:50:53,712 --> 00:50:56,545
Oh, no. Stop, stop!

725
00:50:56,615 --> 00:50:58,742
Hello, Rabbit. I'm Tigger.

726
00:50:58,817 --> 00:51:02,878
- T-I, double "guh"...
- Please! Please! Don't spell it.

727
00:51:02,954 --> 00:51:07,948
Oh, dear. Oh, dear. Just...
Just look at my beautiful garden.

728
00:51:08,026 --> 00:51:10,790
Yuck! And messy, isn't it?

729
00:51:10,862 --> 00:51:14,992
Messy? Messy!
It's ruined! It's ruined, Tigger.

730
00:51:15,067 --> 00:51:19,060
Oh, why don't you ever
stop bouncing?

731
00:51:19,137 --> 00:51:22,595
Why? That's what tiggers do best.

732
00:51:22,674 --> 00:51:25,643
<i>The wonderful thing about tiggers</i>
<i>is tiggers are wonderful things</i>

733
00:51:25,711 --> 00:51:28,475
<i>Their tops are made out of rubber</i>
<i>Their bottoms are made out of springs</i>

734
00:51:28,547 --> 00:51:31,243
<i>They're bouncy, trouncy, flouncy</i>
<i>pouncy, fun, fun, fun, fun, fun</i>

735
00:51:31,316 --> 00:51:33,511
<i>But the most wonderful thing</i>
<i>about tiggers is I'm the only one</i>

736
00:51:33,585 --> 00:51:36,247
<i>I'm the only one</i>

737
00:51:41,860 --> 00:51:44,124
Order. Order, please.

738
00:51:44,196 --> 00:51:50,431
Now, I say Tigger's getting
so bouncy nowadays that
it's time we taught him a lesson.

739
00:51:50,502 --> 00:51:52,800
No matter
how much we like him...

740
00:51:52,871 --> 00:51:56,102
you can't deny
he just bounces too much.

741
00:51:56,174 --> 00:51:58,165
Ah, e-excuse me, Rabbit.

742
00:51:58,243 --> 00:52:03,010
But, uh, perhaps if we could think
of a way of"un-bouncing" Tigger...

743
00:52:03,081 --> 00:52:05,106
well, it would be
a very good idea, huh?

744
00:52:05,183 --> 00:52:10,211
Exactly! Just what I feel.
What do you feel, Pooh?

745
00:52:14,926 --> 00:52:17,360
- Pooh!
- Ah...

746
00:52:17,429 --> 00:52:20,694
Haven't you been listening
to what Rabbit's been saying?

747
00:52:20,766 --> 00:52:26,671
I listened, but then I had
a small piece of fluff in my ear.

748
00:52:26,738 --> 00:52:31,675
- Could you say it again, please, Rabbit?
- Well, where should I start from?

749
00:52:31,743 --> 00:52:34,712
From the moment
the fluff got in my ear.

750
00:52:34,780 --> 00:52:37,078
Well, when was that?

751
00:52:37,149 --> 00:52:40,346
I don't know.
I couldn't hear properly.

752
00:52:40,418 --> 00:52:46,084
Pooh, we were just trying to think of
a way to get the bounce out ofTigger.

753
00:52:46,158 --> 00:52:48,991
Oh, I've got a splendid idea.
Now, listen.

754
00:52:49,060 --> 00:52:52,257
We'll take Tigger
for a long explore, see?

755
00:52:52,330 --> 00:52:54,730
Someplace where he's never been...

756
00:52:54,800 --> 00:52:57,598
- and we lose him there.
- Lose him?

757
00:52:57,669 --> 00:53:00,103
Oh, we'll find him again,
next morning.

758
00:53:00,172 --> 00:53:02,697
And mark my words,
he'll be a humble tigger...

759
00:53:02,774 --> 00:53:04,765
a small-and-sad tigger...

760
00:53:04,843 --> 00:53:08,210
an "Oh, Rabbit,
am-l-glad-to-see-you" tigger.

761
00:53:08,280 --> 00:53:11,272
And it'll take the bounces
out of him, that's why.

762
00:53:11,349 --> 00:53:13,613
Now, all in favor, say, "aye."

763
00:53:13,685 --> 00:53:16,620
Aye. Pooh?

764
00:53:16,688 --> 00:53:19,623
- Pooh!
- Uh, here.

765
00:53:19,691 --> 00:53:23,127
Good. Just good.
Motion carried.

766
00:53:28,033 --> 00:53:31,298
So it was agreed that they
would start the next morning...

767
00:53:31,369 --> 00:53:35,567
which, incidentally,
turned out cold and misty.

768
00:53:40,378 --> 00:53:45,077
Pooh, as usual, had a little
something along to sustain himself.

769
00:53:48,620 --> 00:53:52,989
And now, as Tigger kept bouncing
farther and farther into the mist...

770
00:53:53,058 --> 00:53:56,459
Rabbit thought it was
a good time to lose Tigger.

771
00:53:56,528 --> 00:54:00,555
Now's our chance.
Quick! In here. Hide.

772
00:54:05,904 --> 00:54:08,304
Tigger's lost now, isn't he, Rabbit?

773
00:54:08,373 --> 00:54:11,638
Oh, he's lost, all right, Piglet.

774
00:54:11,710 --> 00:54:15,908
Oh, goody. This is lots of fun, Pooh.

775
00:54:23,755 --> 00:54:27,191
My splendid idea worked.

776
00:54:27,259 --> 00:54:29,693
Now, home we go.

777
00:54:29,761 --> 00:54:33,629
Good! Yum-yum.
It's time for lunch.

778
00:54:33,698 --> 00:54:37,190
- Halloo!
- Oh, my goodness. Hide!

779
00:54:37,269 --> 00:54:40,102
Halloo!

780
00:54:43,508 --> 00:54:46,636
That's funny.
They must be lost.

781
00:54:48,046 --> 00:54:51,538
Hello!

782
00:54:51,616 --> 00:54:57,054
- Hey, you blokes. Where are ya?
- He...

783
00:54:57,122 --> 00:55:00,148
- Shush.
- I am shushed.

784
00:55:00,225 --> 00:55:04,389
Hey, where in the heck
are you guys?

785
00:55:18,710 --> 00:55:20,974
Halloo!

786
00:55:22,247 --> 00:55:26,240
Rabbit? Piglet?
Where are you?

787
00:55:26,318 --> 00:55:28,343
Halloo!

788
00:55:30,322 --> 00:55:33,519
Hooray!
Hooray, we've done it.

789
00:55:33,591 --> 00:55:37,049
Now, come on, hurry.
Let's head for home.

790
00:55:37,128 --> 00:55:40,859
Well, Rabbit was certain that everything
was going according to plan...

791
00:55:40,932 --> 00:55:43,730
and so it seemed to be.

792
00:55:43,802 --> 00:55:45,997
But sometime later...

793
00:55:46,071 --> 00:55:49,905
on the bottom of page 123...

794
00:55:57,282 --> 00:56:01,548
It's a funny thing how everything
looks the same in the mist.

795
00:56:01,619 --> 00:56:05,350
He's right, Piglet.
It's the very same sand pit.

796
00:56:05,423 --> 00:56:07,288
I think so too, Pooh.

797
00:56:07,359 --> 00:56:10,522
Well, it's lucky I know
the forest so well, or...

798
00:56:10,595 --> 00:56:12,688
or, or we might get lost.

799
00:56:12,764 --> 00:56:15,255
Well, come on. Follow me.

800
00:56:15,333 --> 00:56:18,894
Now, Pooh was getting tired
of seeing the same sand pit...

801
00:56:18,970 --> 00:56:22,701
and he suspected it
of following them about.

802
00:56:22,774 --> 00:56:25,971
Because whichever
direction they started in...

803
00:56:26,044 --> 00:56:29,707
they always seemed
to end up at it.

804
00:56:36,354 --> 00:56:38,413
- Uh, er, Rabbit?
- Yes?

805
00:56:38,490 --> 00:56:40,481
Say, Rabbit, how would it be...

806
00:56:40,558 --> 00:56:44,153
if as soon as we're
out of sight of this old pit...

807
00:56:44,229 --> 00:56:48,325
- we just try to find it again?
- What's the good of that?

808
00:56:48,400 --> 00:56:51,301
Well, you see,
we keep looking for home...

809
00:56:51,369 --> 00:56:53,394
but we keep finding this pit.

810
00:56:53,471 --> 00:56:58,340
So I just thought that if we looked
for this pit we might find home.

811
00:56:58,410 --> 00:57:00,742
I don't see much sense in that.

812
00:57:00,812 --> 00:57:02,837
If I walked away from this pit...

813
00:57:02,914 --> 00:57:06,247
and then walked back to it,
of course I should find it.

814
00:57:06,317 --> 00:57:09,411
L'll prove it to you. Wait here.

815
00:57:12,824 --> 00:57:16,157
So Pooh and Piglet
waited in the mist for Rabbit.

816
00:57:16,227 --> 00:57:18,252
And they waited...

817
00:57:18,329 --> 00:57:21,787
and waited, and waited.

818
00:57:21,866 --> 00:57:25,029
And all the while, Pooh's
thoughts kept returning...

819
00:57:25,103 --> 00:57:27,196
to his honey pots at home.

820
00:57:33,044 --> 00:57:35,342
W-W-What was that, Pooh?

821
00:57:35,413 --> 00:57:37,938
My tummy rumbled.

822
00:57:38,016 --> 00:57:40,507
Now then, come on.
Let's go home.

823
00:57:40,585 --> 00:57:43,179
But, Pooh, do you know the way?

824
00:57:43,254 --> 00:57:47,350
No, Piglet, but there are 12 pots
of honey in my cupboard...

825
00:57:47,425 --> 00:57:49,689
and they have been
calling to my tummy.

826
00:57:49,761 --> 00:57:52,491
- They have?
- Yes, Piglet.

827
00:57:52,564 --> 00:57:56,227
I couldn't hear them before
because Rabbit would talk.

828
00:57:56,301 --> 00:57:58,496
I think I know where
they're calling from.

829
00:57:58,570 --> 00:58:02,006
So come on.
We'll just follow my tummy.

830
00:58:02,073 --> 00:58:04,564
Well, they walked off together...

831
00:58:04,642 --> 00:58:07,236
and for a long time
Piglet said nothing...

832
00:58:07,312 --> 00:58:11,043
so as not to interrupt
Pooh's honey pots.

833
00:58:11,116 --> 00:58:14,517
And sure enough,
as the mist got thinner...

834
00:58:14,586 --> 00:58:18,022
and just when Piglet
began to know where he was...

835
00:58:18,089 --> 00:58:22,526
Hey, hello there, you two blokes.
Where have you been?

836
00:58:22,594 --> 00:58:25,028
We've been trying
to find our way back home.

837
00:58:25,096 --> 00:58:29,362
Pooh, I don't think
Rabbit's splendid idea worked.

838
00:58:29,434 --> 00:58:33,200
Say, where is old long-ears, anyway?

839
00:58:33,271 --> 00:58:36,365
He must still be missing
in the mist.

840
00:58:36,441 --> 00:58:40,172
Well, leave it to me.
L'll bounce him out of there!

841
00:58:40,245 --> 00:58:42,770
T-T-F-N. Ta-ta for now.

842
00:58:46,284 --> 00:58:50,550
Meanwhile, Rabbit was still
wandering around in the mist.

843
00:58:50,622 --> 00:58:52,886
By now, he was lost and bewildered.

844
00:58:52,957 --> 00:58:55,289
And to make matters worse...

845
00:58:55,360 --> 00:58:58,887
his mind was beginning
to play tricks on him.

846
00:59:01,633 --> 00:59:04,193
What's that?

847
00:59:09,307 --> 00:59:13,573
Pooh? Piglet?

848
00:59:54,485 --> 00:59:56,419
Help!

849
00:59:56,487 --> 00:59:58,478
- Hello, Rabbit!
- Tigger!

850
00:59:58,556 --> 01:00:00,922
B-B-But you're
supposed to be lost.

851
01:00:00,992 --> 01:00:05,122
Aw, Tiggers never get lost,
bunny boy.

852
01:00:05,196 --> 01:00:07,460
Never get lost?

853
01:00:07,532 --> 01:00:09,693
- Of course not.
- Oh, no.

854
01:00:09,767 --> 01:00:14,363
Come on, Rabbit.
Let's go home. Hang on!

855
01:00:14,439 --> 01:00:20,207
So they started back. And Rabbit
was now a humiliated rabbit...

856
01:00:20,278 --> 01:00:22,610
a lost-and-found rabbit...

857
01:00:22,680 --> 01:00:26,776
an "Oh-why, oh-why-do-these-things
happen-to-me" rabbit.

858
01:00:28,152 --> 01:00:29,949
And now we come to the next chapter...

859
01:00:30,088 --> 01:00:33,819
in which the first snowfall had
covered the Hundred-Acre Wood.

860
01:00:33,891 --> 01:00:39,591
And in which Tigger learns that
even bouncing can be overdone.

861
01:00:39,664 --> 01:00:44,226
On this day, Roo was waiting
for Tigger to take him out to play.

862
01:00:44,302 --> 01:00:47,237
Mama, when is Tigger
gonna get here?

863
01:00:47,305 --> 01:00:50,866
- Be patient, dear. He'll be...
- Whee!

864
01:00:50,942 --> 01:00:55,038
Well, here I am!
Did I surprise you, Roo?

865
01:00:55,113 --> 01:00:57,980
You sure did!
I like surprises.

866
01:00:58,049 --> 01:01:02,179
- Hello, Mrs. Kanga, ma'am.
- Why, hello, Tigger, dear.

867
01:01:02,253 --> 01:01:04,744
She called me "dear."

868
01:01:04,822 --> 01:01:08,189
Roo, are you ready
for some bouncing?

869
01:01:08,259 --> 01:01:10,989
Yeah! You and me
are good bouncers.

870
01:01:11,062 --> 01:01:13,496
Just a moment, dear.

871
01:01:13,564 --> 01:01:17,159
Hold still. Goodness,
you're bouncy today.

872
01:01:17,235 --> 01:01:20,261
That's what roos do the "best-est."

873
01:01:20,338 --> 01:01:24,741
- Now keep your scarf on.
- Not so tight, Mama.

874
01:01:24,809 --> 01:01:27,835
- Is your sweater warm enough?
- Yes, Mother.

875
01:01:27,912 --> 01:01:31,006
Well, come on, Roo. Let's go!

876
01:01:31,082 --> 01:01:34,017
Tigger, have Roo home
in time for his nap.

877
01:01:34,085 --> 01:01:36,679
And be careful!

878
01:01:36,754 --> 01:01:40,588
Don't worry, Mrs. Kanga.
L'll take care of the little nipper.

879
01:01:46,097 --> 01:01:49,066
<i>Da, da, da, da</i>

880
01:01:49,133 --> 01:01:52,102
<i>Da, da, da, da</i>

881
01:01:52,170 --> 01:01:55,105
Ah! What a perfect day!

882
01:01:55,173 --> 01:01:57,403
Peace and quiet...

883
01:01:57,475 --> 01:02:00,706
and thank goodness, no Tigger.

884
01:02:00,778 --> 01:02:05,477
Say, look, look, look.
If it isn't old long-ears.

885
01:02:05,550 --> 01:02:09,077
Can tiggers ice-skate
as fancy as Mr. Rabbit?

886
01:02:09,153 --> 01:02:13,749
Can tiggers ice-skate?
Why, that's what tiggers do the best.

887
01:02:15,159 --> 01:02:17,150
Whee!

888
01:02:18,329 --> 01:02:21,321
Say, this is a cinch.

889
01:02:21,399 --> 01:02:23,833
Whee!

890
01:02:23,901 --> 01:02:27,928
- Oh, no. Not him!
- Uh-oh, look out. I can't... Watch out!

891
01:02:28,005 --> 01:02:30,269
- It can't be!
- Out of the way! Out of the way!

892
01:02:30,341 --> 01:02:33,674
Look out! I can't... Whoa!

893
01:02:40,551 --> 01:02:44,487
Oh, why does it
always have to be me?

894
01:02:44,555 --> 01:02:47,649
Why, oh, why, oh, why?

895
01:02:47,725 --> 01:02:50,319
Tigger, Tigger, are you all right?

896
01:02:52,897 --> 01:02:57,266
Yuck!
Tiggers don't like ice skating.

897
01:02:57,335 --> 01:03:01,863
So Tigger and Roo went farther
into the Hundred-Acre Wood...

898
01:03:01,939 --> 01:03:04,999
Iooking for something
that tiggers do best.

899
01:03:05,076 --> 01:03:08,011
I bet you can climb trees,
huh, Tigger?

900
01:03:08,079 --> 01:03:11,606
Climb trees?
That's what tiggers do best!

901
01:03:11,682 --> 01:03:15,311
Only tiggers don't climb trees.
They bounce them!

902
01:03:15,386 --> 01:03:17,650
Come on, let's go.

903
01:03:24,128 --> 01:03:27,188
I almost bounced
clear out of the book.

904
01:03:27,265 --> 01:03:29,392
Some bouncing, huh?

905
01:03:32,904 --> 01:03:36,067
Say, how did this tree get so high?

906
01:03:38,242 --> 01:03:40,472
Hey. H-H-Hey!

907
01:03:40,545 --> 01:03:43,810
Hey, what's happening now?

908
01:03:43,881 --> 01:03:47,339
Don't swing on a string.
It's much too frail.

909
01:03:47,418 --> 01:03:51,377
The best kind of swing
is a tigger's tail. Whee!

910
01:03:51,456 --> 01:03:54,892
S-S-Stop that, kid. Please.

911
01:03:54,959 --> 01:03:59,396
S-T-O-P, stop.
You're rocking the forest.

912
01:04:01,833 --> 01:04:06,167
- What's the matter, Tigger?
- Whew! Oh, thank goodness.

913
01:04:06,237 --> 01:04:11,265
I was just getting seasick
from seeing too much.

914
01:04:11,342 --> 01:04:15,745
Well, we'll just have to leave Tigger
up in the tree top for a little while.

915
01:04:15,813 --> 01:04:19,214
Because, at the bottom
of the next page...

916
01:04:19,350 --> 01:04:21,318
Pooh is having a problem of his own.

917
01:04:21,385 --> 01:04:24,411
- What are you doing, Pooh?
- Shh!

918
01:04:24,489 --> 01:04:27,754
- Tracking something.
- Tracking what?

919
01:04:27,825 --> 01:04:31,226
Well, that's what I asked myself,
Piglet. What?

920
01:04:33,965 --> 01:04:36,559
And what do you think
you'll answer yourself?

921
01:04:36,634 --> 01:04:39,626
I shall have to wait
until I catch up with it.

922
01:04:39,704 --> 01:04:42,070
Pooh, for a bear
of very little brain...

923
01:04:42,139 --> 01:04:45,131
- you sure are a smart one!
- Thank you, Piglet.

924
01:04:45,209 --> 01:04:47,905
- Aha, ha!
- Oh!

925
01:04:47,979 --> 01:04:50,243
N-N-Now w-w-what?

926
01:04:50,314 --> 01:04:53,909
A very mysterious thing, Piglet.

927
01:04:53,985 --> 01:04:56,920
A whole new set of tracks. See?

928
01:04:56,988 --> 01:04:59,752
And so it seemed to be.

929
01:04:59,824 --> 01:05:02,622
There were the tracks
joining each other here...

930
01:05:02,693 --> 01:05:05,093
getting mixed up
with each other there.

931
01:05:05,162 --> 01:05:10,566
But to Pooh, quite plainly,
four sets of paw marks.

932
01:05:10,635 --> 01:05:14,901
Piglet, whatever it was
that made these tracks...

933
01:05:14,972 --> 01:05:18,135
has now been joined
by a "whatever-it-is."

934
01:05:18,209 --> 01:05:23,511
Y-Y-Yes. A-And all of them
are proceeding in company.

935
01:05:23,581 --> 01:05:26,778
Piglet, I wasn't exactly
expecting company.

936
01:05:26,851 --> 01:05:30,514
N-N-Neither was I, Pooh.

937
01:05:30,588 --> 01:05:34,149
So they went on,
feeling a little anxious now...

938
01:05:34,225 --> 01:05:37,820
in case the animals in front of them
were of hostile intent.

939
01:05:37,895 --> 01:05:39,920
Halloo!

940
01:05:44,201 --> 01:05:46,192
Look, look, Piglet...

941
01:05:46,270 --> 01:05:49,706
there's something
in that tree over there.

942
01:05:49,774 --> 01:05:53,369
- Is it one of the f-f-fiercer animals?
- Halloo!

943
01:05:53,444 --> 01:05:56,709
Yes. It's a "jagular."

944
01:05:56,781 --> 01:06:00,717
W-What do
jagulars d-do, Pooh?

945
01:06:00,785 --> 01:06:06,314
Well, jagulars always call,
"Halloo!"

946
01:06:06,390 --> 01:06:10,622
And when you look up,
they drop on you.

947
01:06:10,695 --> 01:06:12,720
I'm looking down, P-P-Pooh.

948
01:06:12,797 --> 01:06:15,391
Halloo!

949
01:06:15,466 --> 01:06:18,731
Hey, Tigger,
it's Pooh and Piglet.

950
01:06:18,803 --> 01:06:21,397
Pooh! Piglet!

951
01:06:21,472 --> 01:06:26,739
Why, it's only Tigger and Roo.
Come on.

952
01:06:29,480 --> 01:06:34,247
Hello, Roo. Hey, what are you
and Tigger doing up there?

953
01:06:34,318 --> 01:06:38,584
I'm all right,
but Tigger's stuck.

954
01:06:38,656 --> 01:06:41,216
Help, somebody! Please!

955
01:06:41,292 --> 01:06:43,920
Get Christopher Robin.

956
01:06:43,995 --> 01:06:49,262
Well, it wasn't too long before word
got back to Christopher Robin and
the others that Tigger was in trouble.

957
01:06:50,968 --> 01:06:54,597
Hello, Pooh.
Hello, Piglet. What's up?

958
01:06:54,672 --> 01:06:56,936
Tigger and Roo are up...

959
01:06:57,008 --> 01:07:01,274
Oh, my goodness.
Roo, how did you get way up there?

960
01:07:01,345 --> 01:07:04,041
Easy, Mama. We bounced up.

961
01:07:04,115 --> 01:07:06,743
Oh, gracious.
Do be careful, dear.

962
01:07:06,817 --> 01:07:10,583
I'm all right, Mama,
but Tigger's stuck.

963
01:07:10,655 --> 01:07:13,783
Oh, what a shame.
That's too bad.

964
01:07:13,858 --> 01:07:18,454
No, that's good. You see,
he can't bounce anybody up there.

965
01:07:18,529 --> 01:07:21,794
Oh, dear. We'll just have
to get him down somehow.

966
01:07:21,866 --> 01:07:24,630
Down? Down?
Do we have to?

967
01:07:24,702 --> 01:07:28,468
Come on, everyone.
Let's hold the corner of my coat.

968
01:07:28,539 --> 01:07:30,905
You're first, Roo. Jump!

969
01:07:30,975 --> 01:07:33,205
Try not to fall too fast, dear.

970
01:07:33,277 --> 01:07:35,939
Whee!

971
01:07:36,013 --> 01:07:41,110
- Oh, thank goodness.
- Gee, that was fun!

972
01:07:41,185 --> 01:07:44,882
Come on, Tigger.
It doesn't hurt. Jump!

973
01:07:44,955 --> 01:07:49,983
- You're next, Tigger. Jump!
- Jump?

974
01:07:50,061 --> 01:07:53,155
Tiggers don't jump.
They bounce.

975
01:07:53,230 --> 01:07:55,164
Then bounce down.

976
01:07:55,232 --> 01:07:58,827
Don't be "ridiccorous."
Tiggers only bounce up!

977
01:07:58,903 --> 01:08:00,837
You can climb down, Tigger.

978
01:08:00,905 --> 01:08:06,400
Ah, but tiggers can't climb down, uh,
because, uh, their tails get in the way.

979
01:08:06,477 --> 01:08:08,468
Hooray! That settles it.

980
01:08:08,546 --> 01:08:10,912
If he won't jump
and he can't climb down...

981
01:08:10,981 --> 01:08:13,677
then we'll just have to
leave him up there forever!

982
01:08:13,751 --> 01:08:17,448
Forever?
Oh, if I ever get out of this...

983
01:08:17,521 --> 01:08:20,820
I promise never
to bounce again, never!

984
01:08:20,891 --> 01:08:25,328
I heard that, Tigger. He promised!
Did you hear him promise?

985
01:08:25,396 --> 01:08:29,423
I heard him. I heard him!
You heard him, didn't you? Didn't you?

986
01:08:29,500 --> 01:08:34,130
Well, Tigger, your bouncing
really got you into trouble this time.

987
01:08:34,205 --> 01:08:36,298
Say, who are you?

988
01:08:36,373 --> 01:08:38,364
I'm the narrator.

989
01:08:38,442 --> 01:08:41,934
Oh, well, please, for goodness' sakes,
narrate me down from here.

990
01:08:42,012 --> 01:08:45,209
Very well. Hold on tight.

991
01:08:48,419 --> 01:08:50,614
You can let go now, Tigger.

992
01:08:50,688 --> 01:08:53,885
N-N-Never.

993
01:08:53,958 --> 01:08:58,292
But, Tigger, look for yourself.
You're perfectly safe.

994
01:09:04,034 --> 01:09:06,502
What did I tell you, Tigger?

995
01:09:06,570 --> 01:09:09,471
Come on. Back we go.

996
01:09:12,943 --> 01:09:16,071
Oh! Good old terra firma.

997
01:09:17,782 --> 01:09:20,751
Say, I'm so happy,
I feel like bouncing.

998
01:09:20,818 --> 01:09:23,184
Uh-uh-uh!
You promised. You promised.

999
01:09:23,254 --> 01:09:26,690
Oh. Oh, I did, didn't I?

1000
01:09:26,757 --> 01:09:30,193
You mean, I can't ever bounce again?

1001
01:09:30,261 --> 01:09:33,389
- Never!
- Never?

1002
01:09:38,235 --> 01:09:43,036
Not even just one
teensy, weensy bounce?

1003
01:09:43,107 --> 01:09:45,735
Not even a smidgen of a bounce.

1004
01:10:01,859 --> 01:10:06,353
Oh, the poor dear.
Oh, that's too bad.

1005
01:10:10,768 --> 01:10:15,705
Christopher Robin,
I like the old bouncy Tigger best.

1006
01:10:18,442 --> 01:10:23,072
- So do I, Roo.
- I do too.
- Me too!

1007
01:10:23,147 --> 01:10:27,607
Of course, we all do.
Don't you agree, Rabbit?

1008
01:10:29,820 --> 01:10:32,254
- L-l...
- Well, Rabbit?

1009
01:10:32,323 --> 01:10:34,814
Well, I, uh...

1010
01:10:34,892 --> 01:10:37,884
That is, uh...
Uh, what I mean...

1011
01:10:37,962 --> 01:10:42,228
- Well?
- Well, I, ah...

1012
01:10:42,299 --> 01:10:44,392
Oh, all right.

1013
01:10:44,468 --> 01:10:48,598
I guess I like
the old Tigger better too.

1014
01:10:48,672 --> 01:10:53,268
Oh, boy! You mean,
I can have my bounce back?

1015
01:10:53,344 --> 01:10:55,574
Come on, Rabbit.
Let's you and me bounce.

1016
01:10:55,646 --> 01:10:57,978
Good heavens! Me bounce?

1017
01:10:58,048 --> 01:11:00,812
Why, certainly!
Look, you've got the feet for it.

1018
01:11:00,885 --> 01:11:04,685
- I have?
- Sure. Come on, try it.

1019
01:11:04,755 --> 01:11:07,417
It makes you feel just g-g-great!

1020
01:11:07,491 --> 01:11:10,688
- Well, say, it does, doesn't it?
- Yes, it does.

1021
01:11:10,761 --> 01:11:15,664
- Well, come on, everybody, bounce!
- Come on, bounce.

1022
01:11:15,733 --> 01:11:19,499
<i>The wonderful thing about tiggers</i>
<i>is tiggers are wonderful things</i>

1023
01:11:19,570 --> 01:11:22,095
<i>Their tops are made out of rubber</i>
<i>Their bottoms are made out of springs</i>

1024
01:11:22,172 --> 01:11:24,834
<i>They're bouncy, trouncy, flouncy</i>
<i>pouncy fun, fun, fun, fun, fun</i>

1025
01:11:24,909 --> 01:11:27,343
<i>But the most wonderful thing</i>
<i>about tiggers is I'm the only one</i>

1026
01:11:27,411 --> 01:11:29,606
<i>I'm the only one</i>

1027
01:11:36,020 --> 01:11:38,818
And so, we come to the last chapter...

1028
01:11:38,889 --> 01:11:43,349
in which Christopher Robin and Pooh
come to the enchanted place...

1029
01:11:43,427 --> 01:11:45,861
- and we say good-bye.
- Good-bye?

1030
01:11:45,930 --> 01:11:49,730
Oh, no, please, can't we go back
to page one and do it all over again?

1031
01:11:49,800 --> 01:11:54,066
Sorry, Pooh, but all stories
have an ending, you know.

1032
01:11:54,138 --> 01:11:56,163
Oh, bother.

1033
01:11:56,240 --> 01:11:58,800
Yes, the time had come at last.

1034
01:11:58,876 --> 01:12:01,868
Christopher Robin
was going away to school.

1035
01:12:01,946 --> 01:12:06,383
Nobody else in the forest knew
exactly why or where he was going.

1036
01:12:06,450 --> 01:12:11,012
All they knew was it had something
to do with "twice times"...

1037
01:12:11,088 --> 01:12:14,421
and how to make things
called "A-B-C's"...

1038
01:12:14,491 --> 01:12:18,723
and where a place called Brazil is.

1039
01:12:20,097 --> 01:12:22,088
- Pooh?
- Huh?

1040
01:12:22,166 --> 01:12:25,602
What do you like doing
best in the world?

1041
01:12:25,669 --> 01:12:28,604
What I like best
is me going to visit you...

1042
01:12:28,672 --> 01:12:33,575
and you saying,
"How about a smackerel of honey?"

1043
01:12:33,644 --> 01:12:36,112
I like that too.

1044
01:12:36,180 --> 01:12:39,581
But what I like best
is just doing nothing.

1045
01:12:39,650 --> 01:12:43,211
- How do you do "just nothing"?
- Well...

1046
01:12:43,287 --> 01:12:46,552
it's when grown-ups ask,
"What are you going to do?"

1047
01:12:46,623 --> 01:12:50,423
And you say, "nothing."
Then you go out and do it.

1048
01:12:50,494 --> 01:12:52,894
I like that.
Let's do it all the time.

1049
01:12:52,963 --> 01:12:55,932
You know something, Pooh...

1050
01:12:56,000 --> 01:12:58,696
I'm not going to do
just nothing anymore.

1051
01:12:58,769 --> 01:13:00,760
You mean, never again?

1052
01:13:00,838 --> 01:13:03,363
Well, not so much.

1053
01:13:03,440 --> 01:13:05,431
Pooh...

1054
01:13:05,509 --> 01:13:08,034
when I'm away
just doing nothing...

1055
01:13:08,112 --> 01:13:10,103
will you come up here sometimes?

1056
01:13:10,180 --> 01:13:12,774
You mean, alone?

1057
01:13:12,850 --> 01:13:15,284
- Just me?
- Yes.

1058
01:13:15,352 --> 01:13:18,879
And, Pooh, promise
you won't forget me...

1059
01:13:18,956 --> 01:13:21,948
- ever?
- Oh, I won't, Christopher, I promise.

1060
01:13:22,026 --> 01:13:24,221
Not even when I'm a hundred?

1061
01:13:24,294 --> 01:13:26,558
How old shall I be then?

1062
01:13:26,630 --> 01:13:28,723
Ninety-nine.

1063
01:13:28,799 --> 01:13:30,926
Silly old bear.

1064
01:13:31,001 --> 01:13:33,265
Wherever they go...

1065
01:13:33,337 --> 01:13:36,306
and whatever happens
to them on the way...

1066
01:13:36,373 --> 01:13:40,070
in that enchanted place
on top of the forest...

1067
01:13:40,144 --> 01:13:42,772
a little bear
will always be waiting.